`,e.jsxs(s.p,{children:['Imagine a cardiologist seeing a patient for the first time. Before ordering any scans, she runs through a sequence of focused questions: "Is the patient over 50?" If yes — "Does the patient smoke?" If yes — "Is blood pressure above 140 mmHg?" By the time she reaches a conclusion, she has followed a branching chain of conditions, each one narrowing the diagnostic space until a single leaf node is reached: ',e.jsx(s.em,{children:"high cardiovascular risk, refer to specialist"}),"."]}),`
`,e.jsx(s.p,{children:"This is not just a metaphor. It is literally a decision tree encoded in expert reasoning. The doctor's protocol can be drawn as a graph, transcribed into pseudocode, and fit to data. Decision trees make this explicit and learnable from examples."}),`
`,e.jsx(s.p,{children:"Now consider why a linear model fails in this setting. A logistic regression draws a single hyperplane to separate classes. In many real problems, the boundary is not a straight line. Consider XOR-patterned data: points are labeled positive when both features are high or both are low, and negative otherwise. No straight line can separate these classes — the decision boundary is inherently non-linear and axis-aligned."}),`
`,e.jsxs(s.p,{children:[e.jsx(s.strong,{children:"The XOR problem:"})," A dataset where class 1 occupies quadrants (high x1, high x2) and (low x1, low x2), and class 0 occupies the other two quadrants, is not linearly separable. A logistic regression trained on it achieves roughly 50% accuracy. A depth-2 decision tree perfectly separates it with two axis-aligned cuts. This is a fundamental structural advantage."]}),`
`,e.jsx(k,{children:e.jsxs(s.p,{children:[e.jsx(s.strong,{children:"From intuition to formalism."})," The doctor's diagnostic protocol is informal — passed on through training, refined by experience. A decision tree algorithm formalizes the same process: it learns the sequence of questions and thresholds from labeled data, selecting at each step the question that most cleanly separates the classes. The result is a model that is both interpretable (you can read it like a flowchart) and mathematically precise (it defines a piecewise-constant function over the feature space). The next section lays out the anatomy of that structure."]})}),`
